The paper addresses the problem of establishing semantic correspondences between images, which is a common task in computer vision. The proposed approach uses a convolutional neural network architecture, which is a popular technique in the field of computer vision and falls under the cs.CV sub-category. Additionally, the approach involves learning a geometrically plausible model for semantic correspondence, which suggests that it may also fall under the cs.LG sub-category, which deals with machine learning techniques. The paper also mentions that the proposed approach outperforms previous methods based on hand-crafted features, which suggests that it may fall under the cs.AI sub-category, which deals with artificial intelligence techniques. Finally, the paper evaluates the proposed approach on several standard benchmarks, which suggests that it may also fall under the cs.MM and cs.IR sub-categories, which deal with multimedia and information retrieval techniques, respectively.
